	<paragraphs xml:id="stacking-matrices">
	<title><insert>Stacking Matrices</insert></title><p/>

		<p>
			Finally, we can create "block" matrices from smaller matrices by treating them as elements themselves and using the comma (or space) and the semicolon to create rows and columns.  We just have to make sure the dimensions of the matrices line up properly.  For example, we can stack two matrices.
		</p>

		<example xml:id="ex_stackmatrices"><p/>
		<title><em><term>Stacking Matrices</term></em></title><p/>

			<sidebyside width="100%">
				<program language="matlab">
					<code>
							&gt;&gt; A = [1 2 3 4; 5 6 7 8]; B = [1;  6;  0;  9]; 
							&gt;&gt; AoverBprime = [A ;  B']
					</code>
				</program>
			</sidebyside>

			<sidebyside width="100%">
				<program language="matlab">
					<code>
							AoverBprime = 
								1 2 3 4
								5 6 7 8
								1 6 0 9
					</code>
				</program>
			</sidebyside>
		</example>

	</paragraphs>

